DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
The philosophical literature on racial and ethnic profiling divides into three main clusters. The first concerns the epistemic-statistical question: can probabilistic inferences about group-level crime rates justify differential police scrutiny? Risse and Zeckhauser (2004) defend a qualified pro-profiling position grounded in consequentialist and actuarial reasoning, provoking sustained replies from Lever (2005, 2007), Williams (2010), and Mogensen (2017). Harcourt (2004, 2006) mounts the most thorough empirical and analytical attack on this tradition, showing that actuarial profiling produces elastic offsetting responses (criminals switch to less-profiled groups), degrades community cooperation, and rests on contested benchmark assumptions about the base-rate distribution of crime. Schauer (2009) defends the general rationality of generalisation-based reasoning while acknowledging its moral tensions. The second cluster addresses the normative wrongness of profiling independently of its accuracy. Hellman (2008) and Eidelson (2015) ground the wrong in the expressive meaning of demeaning treatment. Lippert-Rasmussen (2006, 2010, 2013) argues for a sophisticated anti-statistical-discrimination position while acknowledging that individual vs. group-based treatment creates genuine moral complexity. Hosein (2018) adds a political-status dimension: profiling conveys to the profiled that they are second-class members of the polity, a wrong independent of its epistemic credentials. Bou-Habib (2011) and Mogensen (2017) introduce considerations of cumulative injustice when profiling compounds pre-existing racial disadvantage. The third cluster, less developed, addresses epistemic vices and structural ignorance: when does a formally valid probabilistic inference rest on corrupted inputs? Fricker's (2007) framework of testimonial injustice provides one vocabulary; DeAngelis (2014) frames the wrong in terms of the communicative violation of the presumption of innocence; Atenasio (2020) challenges the epistemic rationality claim using criminological evidence showing race is a poor baseline compared to socioeconomic variables.

The Bayesian feedback-loop project maps onto this literature in a distinctive way. The classical pro-profiling argument assumes that observed hit rates track real group-level differences in underlying propensity. The feedback analysis exposes why this assumption is defeated: the hit-rate signal is itself endogenous to who is stopped and at what rate. Harcourt (2004) gestures at this with his ratchet/offsetting argument, but does not model the Simpson's-paradox mechanism whereby poverty confounds the apparent race-crime correlation. Maitzen (1991) and Lippert-Rasmussen (2010) provide older philosophical treatments of statistical discrimination that the project can use as foils.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain supplies the normative stakes of the Bayesian feedback model. If profiling were epistemically sound, its wrongness would need to rest on non-epistemic grounds (dignity, equal status). The project's contribution is to show that the epistemic justification itself is defeated by endogeneity and confounding -- that poverty drives behaviour, not group membership, and that differential sampling rates make the observed hit-rate appear to confirm prior racial beliefs even when the underlying data disconfirm them. This supports a unified critique in which profiling is both epistemically vicious and morally wrong.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
The philosophical literature contains little sustained engagement with the mechanisms of feedback-driven belief updating in Bayesian terms; most discussion of self-fulfilling prophecy is qualitative and descriptive. Shelby's work on the ethics of poverty and criminality -- which is relevant to the confounding-by-poverty mechanism -- is not directly engaged with in the profiling literature. INCOMPLETE entries (abstract not available from any source): harcourt2004rethinking, harcourt2006against, lippertrasmussen2010we, lippertrasmussen2006badness, hosein2018racial, maitzen1991ethics, sesardic2018racial -- these remain in the BibTeX for reference but are excluded from synthesis.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Lead with the Risse-Zeckhauser / Harcourt disagreement as the central debate, then show how the modelling project dissolves rather than adjudicates it by making the epistemic premise untenable. Use the dignity/status literature (Hosein, Eidelson, Hellman) to establish that even if the epistemic premise were sound, there would remain independent moral objections.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Pro-profiling (qualified): 4 papers -- Risse & Zeckhauser (2004), Risse (2007), Schauer (2009), Sesardic (2018)
- Anti-profiling (epistemic): 4 papers -- Harcourt (2004, 2006), Atenasio (2020), Maitzen (1991)
- Anti-profiling (dignity/status): 5 papers -- Lever (2005, 2007), Hosein (2018), DeAngelis (2014), Eidelson (2015)
- Anti-profiling (cumulative injustice): 2 papers -- Bou-Habib (2011), Mogensen (2017)
- General framework: 3 papers -- Fricker (2007), Lippert-Rasmussen (2006, 2010, 2013), Williams (2010)
====================================================================
}

@comment{
====================================================================
DOMAIN: Statistical Discrimination, Feedback Loops, and Self-Confirming Beliefs
SEARCH_DATE: 2026-03-03
PAPERS_FOUND: 19 total (High: 11, Medium: 6, Low: 2)
SEARCH_SOURCES: SEP, PhilPapers, Semantic Scholar, OpenAlex, CORE, CrossRef, WebSearch
====================================================================

DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
The domain of statistical discrimination originates with Phelps (1972) and Arrow (1973),
who independently showed that even profit-maximizing, non-prejudiced employers will
discriminate by group when group membership is a low-cost proxy for unobservable individual
productivity. Phelps modelled employers who use race or sex as a signal when individual
test scores are noisy; Arrow integrated this into a theory distinguishing taste-based from
statistical discrimination. The central puzzle in the subsequent literature concerns
persistence: why do discriminatory beliefs not correct themselves as agents accumulate
experience? Coate and Loury (1993) gave the canonical answer in a game-theoretic model
where employers' beliefs about minority workers' investment create investment incentives
that make those beliefs self-confirming. Their model has multiple Nash equilibria -- in
one, employers have low expectations and minority workers rationally under-invest; in the
other, expectations are high and investment follows. The discriminatory equilibrium
persists precisely because agents' on-path experience provides no evidence against it.

The game-theoretic underpinning of this persistence is formalised in the concept of
self-confirming equilibrium (Fudenberg and Levine 1993), which generalises Nash
equilibrium to allow incorrect off-path beliefs to survive because they are never tested.
Esponda (2008) and Esponda and Pouzo (2016) extend this to environments where agents
also hold misspecified structural models, yielding Berk-Nash equilibrium -- agents who
misattribute causation (e.g. attribute poverty-driven behaviour to race) will converge to
beliefs that are the best fit to endogenously generated data, even if those beliefs are
structurally wrong. Fudenberg and Levine (2006) explore when rational learning can escape
self-confirming traps -- the answer depends on whether off-path actions are taken and
generate contradictory evidence.

In policing, these mechanisms create a distinctive feedback loop analysed by Harcourt
(2004, 2007): directing enforcement toward a profiled group generates more arrests in
that group, which appears to confirm that group's elevated crime rate, which justifies
continued profiling. Knox, Lowe and Mummolo (2020) formalise the identification problem:
administrative records only capture contact that has occurred, so if initial contact is
itself discriminatory, all subsequent statistics are contaminated -- traditional estimators
can mask or reverse the true direction of bias. This connects to Gelman, Fagan and Kiss
(2007) on stop-and-frisk data and Knowles, Persico and Todd (2001) on vehicle searches,
both of which engage the hit-rate test as a benchmark for neutrality. The research project's
specific contribution -- showing that poverty (not group membership) is the actual driver,
with the group correlation arising from compositional confounding -- is the core Simpson's
paradox insight. Merton's (1948) original account of self-fulfilling prophecy provides
the sociological archetype for this entire class of mechanisms.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain provides the formal foundations for the Bayesian feedback loop model at the
core of the research project. The Coate-Loury model is the direct ancestor: discriminatory
expectations generate confirming investment data. The project extends this logic to policing,
where the confound is compositional (group membership correlates with poverty, poverty with
the behaviour) rather than strategic (groups adjust investment in response to discrimination).
The self-confirming equilibrium literature explains why Bayesian updating from biased samples
does not self-correct -- the very act of profiling determines which data is observed,
making the feedback loop epistemically opaque to the agents inside it.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
The formal literature on statistical discrimination in policing -- as opposed to labour
markets -- remains thinner than warranted; most formal models treat the policing setting
only informally. Starr's Harvard Civil Rights piece on statistical discrimination in
criminal justice (2023) and the Lippert-Rasmussen literature on the ethics of statistical
discrimination address the normative dimension but lack formal Bayesian models of the
feedback mechanism. The cross-domain connection between labour-market statistical
discrimination and policing discrimination has rarely been modelled jointly.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
The synthesis should trace the formal genealogy from Phelps/Arrow through Coate-Loury to
Fudenberg-Levine SCE, before showing how the policing context introduces a structural
identification problem (Knox et al.) that makes the discrimination invisible from within.
The project's Simpson's paradox framing should be positioned as a specific instantiation
of the compositional confound underlying statistical discrimination generally.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Labour-market statistical discrimination: 4 papers -- Phelps, Arrow, Coate-Loury, Fang-Moro survey
- Self-confirming equilibrium (formal): 4 papers -- Fudenberg-Levine (1993, 2006), Esponda (2008), Esponda-Pouzo (2016)
- Racial profiling and policing feedback: 5 papers -- Harcourt (2004, 2007), Gelman et al., Knox et al., Knowles-Persico-Todd
- Normative/philosophical: 3 papers -- Merton, Lippert-Rasmussen, de Bruin
- Empirical foundations: 2 papers -- Pager-Shepherd, Fryer
====================================================================
}

@comment{
====================================================================
DOMAIN: Simpson's Paradox --- Statistical and Philosophical Dimensions
SEARCH_DATE: 2026-03-03
PAPERS_FOUND: 17 total (High: 9, Medium: 7, Low: 1)
SEARCH_SOURCES: SEP, PhilPapers, Semantic Scholar, OpenAlex, CrossRef
====================================================================

DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
Simpson's paradox names the phenomenon in which an association between
two variables in an aggregate population reverses (or disappears) when
the population is partitioned by a third variable. The philosophical
literature distinguishes three layers: (1) the purely mathematical
fact, which is unproblematic given Boole's inequality; (2) the
epistemic question of why the reversal surprises reasoners; and (3) the
normative question of which aggregate or stratum-level statistic is the
"correct" one to report or act on. The first modern treatment, Simpson
(1951), observed the phenomenon in contingency tables. Yule (1903)
anticipated related issues in association analysis. Blyth (1972)
introduced the label "Simpson's paradox" and connected it to Savage's
Sure-Thing Principle. Otte (1985) gave an early philosophical treatment
linking it to probabilistic theories of causality: if C raises the
probability of E in all partitions but lowers it overall, which statistic
captures the "true" causal connection? Cartwright (1979) placed the
paradox within the broader project of distinguishing effective strategies
from mere correlations, arguing that causal claims cannot be read off
population-level correlations alone.

The dominant resolution in contemporary philosophy of causation employs
directed acyclic graphs (DAGs) and do-calculus: Pearl (1995, 2009, 2014)
argues that whether to use aggregated or disaggregated data depends on
the causal structure -- specifically whether the partitioning variable Z
is a confounder (common cause, requiring stratification) or a collider
(common effect, prohibiting stratification). Spirtes, Glymour, and
Scheines (2000) develop the broader graphical causal modelling framework
that underpins this analysis. Armistead (2014) offers a dissent,
arguing that Pearl's purely causal resolution is too narrow and that
noncausal third variables can still carry evidential weight. The
Hernan-Clayton-Keiding (2011) paper demonstrates in an epidemiological
context that the paradox dissolves once the causal structure is made
explicit, serving as a methodological illustration.

Dong, Cai, and Zhao (2024) extend Pearl's approach to show that
Simpson's reversal can arise from several distinct causal graph
structures beyond simple confounding, complicating the diagnosis and
resolution. Fitelson (2017) provides a Bayesian confirmation-theoretic
explanation: the paradox exploits an ambiguity between suppositional and
conjunctive readings of confirmation statements. Bandyopadhyay et al.
(2011) offer a logic-centred analysis distinguishing the paradox's
mathematical, probabilistic, and causal dimensions. Kievit et al.
(2013) document its frequency and consequences in psychological research,
arguing for explicit multi-level modelling as the practical remedy.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
The research project models statistical profiling as a feedback loop:
an official omits income (the true confounder) and uses group membership
as a proxy, generating observed hit rates that appear to justify the
initial bias. This is a precise instance of Simpson's paradox --
poverty is a common cause of both group membership (in the relevant
subpopulation) and of the targeted behaviour, so aggregating over
it produces a spurious group-level association. The causal-graphical
literature (Pearl, Spirtes-Glymour-Scheines) directly supplies the
vocabulary for diagnosing which variable must be adjusted for; the
debate between Pearl and Armistead illuminates what happens when the
official cannot or will not identify the confounding variable; and the
Kievit et al. and Hernan et al. papers demonstrate real-world
consequences of ignoring the paradox in institutional contexts closely
analogous to policing.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
The literature contains substantial work on detecting and resolving
the paradox but relatively little on the normative and political economy
of institutional actors who systematically omit known confounders -- the
exact scenario the research project addresses. The connection between
Simpson's paradox and self-reinforcing statistical discrimination (as
distinct from one-shot bias) is also under-explored in the philosophical
literature.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Emphasise the DAG-based resolution as the theoretical backbone, then
use the Armistead--Pearl exchange to motivate why it matters practically
whether an agent recognises the confound; the profiling loop is precisely
a case where the "third variable" (income) is available but omitted.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Causal-graphical resolution (Pearl, Spirtes et al.): 5 papers -- the
  paradox is dissolved by identifying confounders vs. colliders in the DAG
- Probabilistic/confirmation-theoretic analysis (Otte, Fitelson,
  Eells): 4 papers -- the paradox exposes failures in probabilistic
  theories of causation and Bayesian confirmation
- Statistical/mathematical characterisation (Simpson, Blyth, Good-Mittal,
  Yule): 4 papers -- foundational mathematical description of the paradox
- Applied/methodological (Bickel et al., Hernan et al., Kievit et al.,
  Armistead): 4 papers -- practical consequences in real data contexts
====================================================================
}

@comment{
====================================================================
DOMAIN: Bayesian Epistemology, Biased Evidence, and Belief Revision
SEARCH_DATE: 2026-03-03
PAPERS_FOUND: 18 total (High: 8, Medium: 7, Low: 3)
SEARCH_SOURCES: SEP, IEP, PhilPapers, Semantic Scholar, OpenAlex, CORE, arXiv, CrossRef
====================================================================

DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
Bayesian epistemology is the dominant formal framework for modeling rational belief revision, built on the thesis that degrees of belief (credences) should conform to the probability calculus and be updated by conditionalization: upon learning evidence E, set P_new(H) = P_old(H|E). The normative core of this framework -- Kolmogorov's axioms plus the conditionalization rule -- is standardly justified through Dutch book arguments (Skyrms 1987), accuracy-dominance arguments (Greaves and Wallace 2006), and representation theorems. However, this framework assumes that the evidence stream is exogenous to the agent's prior beliefs. When this assumption is violated -- as in cases of biased sampling, endogenous evidence, or data-generating processes shaped by prior beliefs -- standard Bayesian conditionalization becomes epistemically problematic.

Several pathologies have been identified. First, the "zero-raising problem": if an agent assigns prior probability zero to some hypothesis, no amount of evidence can raise it. This means false certainties are epistemically immune to revision (Raidl 2020). Second, confirmatory bias in belief-updating, formalized by Rabin and Schrag (1999) as an economic model in which agents systematically misread disconfirming signals, creating a self-reinforcing feedback loop. Third, base rate neglect: the tendency to underweight prior probabilities in favor of individuating information (Tversky and Kahneman 1974; Magnus and Callender 2004). Fourth, when the data-generating process itself is endogenous to an agent's prior beliefs -- as in Nimark and Sundaresan's (2019) model of rational inattention -- Bayesian agents may rationally choose evidence sources that reinforce their priors, producing permanent belief polarization.

The literature on "epistemic pathologies of Bayesianism" reveals a fundamental tension between coherence and accuracy. An agent can be formally coherent (respecting probability axioms and updating by conditionalization) while converging on false beliefs, when the evidence they encounter is systematically shaped by their prior beliefs. Vassend (2026) has identified conditions under which Bayesian conditionalization is ecologically suboptimal; Gallow (2019) has shown that externalist Bayesians who conditionalize on biased evidence risk "deliberate self-delusion." These concerns are directly relevant to the profiling feedback loop model: an agent who acts on racial priors generates the very evidence patterns that confirm those priors, yet remains formally Bayesian throughout.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
The profiling feedback loop research requires a formal Bayesian framework to show how discriminatory priors, combined with endogenous evidence selection, generate self-reinforcing belief entrenchment. This domain provides: (a) the normative foundations of Bayesian conditionalization and their limits, (b) formal models of confirmatory bias and its entrenchment of false beliefs, (c) the base rate neglect literature showing how prior stereotypes distort individual case assessment, and (d) philosophical analyses of when formally valid Bayesian updating is nonetheless epistemically vicious. Together, these ground the claim that profiling is not merely unjust but also constitutes an epistemically self-undermining practice.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
The philosophical literature on the interaction between endogenous evidence and Bayesian updating remains underdeveloped -- most treatments focus on psychological bias rather than structurally generated feedback loops. The literature connecting formal Bayesian epistemology to discriminatory institutional practices (profiling) is sparse; Lloyd (2021) is a notable exception but does not address the feedback loop mechanism. Formal models of "selection effect" biases in Bayesian frameworks -- where the evidence available is a non-random function of prior actions -- are more developed in economics than philosophy. INCOMPLETE entries: arntzenius2003problems has no abstract in any database; it remains in the bibliography but will be excluded from synthesis. The substantive note field describes its argument based on known content.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
The synthesis should emphasize the distinction between three levels of Bayesian failure in the profiling context: (1) violations of the probability axioms (incoherence), (2) formally coherent but epistemically vicious updating on endogenous evidence (the main target), and (3) base rate neglect as a third distinct failure mode. Position the profiling feedback loop as an instance of type (2), drawing on Rabin-Schrag and Nimark-Sundaresan for formal models, and Arntzenius, Vassend, and Gallow for the philosophical analysis of conditionalization's limits.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Pro-conditionalization orthodoxy: [3 papers] - Defends Bayesian norms as normatively binding (Skyrms, Greaves-Wallace, Briggs-Pettigrew)
- Limits of conditionalization: [6 papers] - Identifies pathological cases (Arntzenius, Bacchus et al., Raidl, Vassend, Gallow, Meacham)
- Formal models of confirmatory bias: [3 papers] - Economic/formal models (Rabin-Schrag, Nimark-Sundaresan, Ortoleva)
- Heuristics and base rate failure: [2 papers] - Cognitive science connections (Tversky-Kahneman, Magnus-Callender)
- Applied epistemology of profiling: [2 papers] - Direct connections to discrimination (Lloyd, Van Doorn)
- Reference works: [2 papers] - Textbook and comprehensive treatments (Bovens-Hartmann, Titelbaum)
====================================================================
}

@comment{
====================================================================
DOMAIN: Poverty, Race, and the Empirical Structure of Policing
SEARCH_DATE: 2026-03-03
PAPERS_FOUND: 17 total (High: 10, Medium: 6, Low: 1)
SEARCH_SOURCES: SEP, PhilPapers, Semantic Scholar, OpenAlex, CORE, CrossRef (verification)
====================================================================

DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain covers the empirical and structural literature on the relationship
between poverty, race, and criminal justice outcomes in the United States.
The central intellectual dispute is whether racial disparities in arrest,
incarceration, and police contact reflect differential behaviour (the
"differential involvement" hypothesis) or differential enforcement
(the "differential selection" hypothesis) or both interacting with structural
disadvantage. The foundational synthesis, associated with Sampson and Wilson
(1995) and elaborated in Sampson (1997, 2018, 2025), argues that concentrated
poverty and racial segregation -- not race per se -- are the proximate causes
of elevated crime rates in racially identifiable communities. This structural
account challenges the inference from racially skewed enforcement statistics
to racially differentiated behaviour.

The second major strand concerns how policing itself generates the statistics
used to justify it. Harcourt (2004, 2007) shows that actuarial profiling
creates a feedback loop: intensive surveillance of profiled communities
produces higher arrest rates, which then justify further intensive surveillance,
while generating underestimates of crime in non-profiled communities. Knox,
Lowe & Mummolo (2020) provide the formal statistical argument: administrative
records produced by selective enforcement are fundamentally biased samples of
underlying behaviour, making traditional estimators of racial bias in policing
statistically non-identified. Gelman, Fagan & Kiss (2007) demonstrate this
empirically for the NYPD stop-and-frisk programme.

The third strand -- represented by Western & Pettit (2010), Wacquant (2009),
Garland (2023), and Lee (2024) -- traces the structural conditions that produce
mass incarceration: deindustrialisation, concentrated poverty, racial
segregation, and the political economy of crime control. These accounts explain
why the targeted group (low-income Black men in particular) contains a
disproportionate share of the poor, which is the key structural premise of
the Bayesian profiling model.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
The Bayesian feedback-loop model assumes that poverty, not group membership,
drives the underlying infraction rate, but that the targeted group contains a
disproportionately high share of the poor. This domain provides the empirical
grounding for both assumptions: the poverty-crime nexus literature establishes
the first premise, while the structural incarceration and neighbourhood-effects
literature explains how racial stratification places the poor disproportionately
within racially defined groups. The enforcement-bias literature (Knox et al.,
Gelman et al., Harcourt) establishes that observed statistics are artefacts of
enforcement intensity rather than underlying behaviour -- the central mechanism
the model seeks to formalise.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
The literature on feedback dynamics in policing is largely qualitative or
simulation-based; formal Bayesian models of how profiling intensity and arrest
statistics co-evolve remain sparse. The Pettit (2012) book on statistical
invisibility of incarcerated populations could not be fully verified for a
journal article form; it is cited here from a CORE-sourced summary.
Several papers (Fryer 2016) are contested and should be read alongside
methodological critiques; the Knox et al. (2020) response is the best available
rebuttal.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
The strongest synthesis narrative runs from structural poverty (Wilson, Sampson-
Wilson) through differential police deployment (Soss-Weaver) to enforcement-
biased statistics (Knox et al., Gelman et al.) to cumulative disadvantage
(Kurlychek-Johnson, Western et al. 2021) and back to structural reproduction
(Wacquant, Garland). This loop maps directly to the feedback structure of the
Bayesian model.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Structural/poverty account: 6 papers -- poverty and segregation, not race
  as such, drive crime and enforcement patterns (Sampson, Wilson, Wacquant,
  Garland, Western-Pettit, Lee)
- Enforcement-bias account: 4 papers -- police statistics are artefacts of
  selective surveillance (Knox-Lowe-Mummolo, Gelman-Fagan-Kiss, Harcourt,
  Fagan-Davies)
- Cumulative disadvantage account: 3 papers -- compounding of disadvantage
  across criminal justice stages reinforces structural inequality (Kurlychek-
  Johnson, Western et al. 2021, Lee-Gibbons-Baker-Wildeman)
- Contested/benchmark: 1 paper (Fryer 2016) -- benchmark study claiming no
  racial disparity in officer-involved shootings; methodologically contested
====================================================================
}

@comment{
====================================================================
DOMAIN: Algorithmic Fairness, Formal Models of Bias, and Machine Learning Ethics
SEARCH_DATE: 2026-03-03
PAPERS_FOUND: 18 total (High: 8, Medium: 8, Low: 2)
SEARCH_SOURCES: SEP, PhilPapers, Semantic Scholar, OpenAlex, CORE, arXiv
====================================================================

DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain encompasses the rapidly growing literature on formal fairness criteria
for machine learning systems, the incompatibility theorems that govern them, and
the philosophical debates about what algorithmic fairness requires. Three
statistical criteria have dominated debate: demographic parity (equal rates of
positive predictions across groups), equalised odds/equality of opportunity
(equal true-positive and false-positive rates), and calibration (predicted
probabilities correspond to actual outcome rates within groups). A central
finding -- proved independently by Chouldechova (2017) and Kleinberg, Mullainathan
and Raghavan (2016) -- is that these criteria are mutually incompatible whenever
base rates differ across groups, yielding an impossibility theorem whose bearing
on real criminal-justice tools like COMPAS has generated extensive philosophical
analysis (Hedden 2021, Eva 2022, Beigang 2023, Lippert-Rasmussen 2024).

The second major strand covers feedback loops and self-reinforcing bias in
predictive policing. Ensign et al. (2017) proved mathematically that predictive
policing systems trained on discovered crime data (arrests, stops) exhibit runaway
feedback: the algorithm sends officers to neighbourhoods historically policed,
generating new discovered crime precisely there, which feeds back into training
data and concentrates patrol further. Lum and Isaac (2016) showed empirically with
PREDPOL that these loops replicate and amplify racial disparities from drug arrests.
Akpinar, De-Arteaga and Chouldechova (2021) extended this analysis to victim-
reported crime data, showing that differential reporting rates alone generate
outcome disparities independent of feedback. Richardson, Schultz and Crawford
(2019) documented how civil rights violations (illegal stop-and-frisk, racial
profiling) contaminate the training data used by predictive policing systems,
creating a causal chain from past discrimination to algorithmic discrimination.

A third strand addresses proxy discrimination and omitted variable bias. Barocas
and Selbst (2016) analysed how seemingly neutral variables can serve as proxies
for protected characteristics, permitting disparate impact through facially
neutral models. Dwork et al. (2012) proposed "fairness through awareness" as an
alternative framework requiring individual fairness: similar individuals should
receive similar predictions. Philosophical literature (Hellman 2020, Hu 2024,
Babic and Johnson King 2023) has increasingly focused on what racial and other
categories mean in algorithmic contexts and whether statistical criteria capture
the morally relevant dimensions of discrimination.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
The research idea constructs a Bayesian model of how profiling generates a self-
reinforcing feedback loop via Simpson's paradox; this domain provides (a) the
mathematical impossibility results showing that formal fairness criteria cannot
simultaneously be satisfied, directly bearing on whether the profiling feedback
loop can be corrected by metric optimisation; (b) the formal and empirical
literature on predictive policing feedback loops (Ensign et al., Lum and Isaac,
Akpinar et al.) which are the principal real-world instantiation of the mechanism
the project models; and (c) the proxy discrimination literature showing how
omission of relevant variables compounds bias, which connects to the project's
focus on training-data selection and Simpson's paradox.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
The formal literature on feedback loops focuses on place-based hot-spot policing
rather than person-based profiling (stop-and-frisk, racial profiling of
individuals), which is the project's central concern; the connection between
individual-level Bayesian updating and group-level feedback loops is undertheorised.
Abstracts were unavailable for: hardt2016equality (NeurIPS preprint), richardson2019dirty
(law review), eva2022algorithmic (Philosophy & Public Affairs), hellman2020measuring
(Virginia Law Review), babic2023algorithmic (Philosophical Studies).

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
The synthesis should distinguish the impossibility theorems (static, single-round)
from the feedback-loop literature (dynamic, iterative); the project's Bayesian
model bridges these, and that connection should be foregrounded. The COMPAS debate
provides a concrete political and normative context for the impossibility results.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Calibration-prioritising view: [Chouldechova, Kleinberg et al., Pleiss et al.] --
  calibration is the primary fairness requirement; false-positive parity cannot
  be simultaneously satisfied
- Equalised odds view: [Hardt et al., Hedden, Lippert-Rasmussen] -- equal error
  rates across groups are the appropriate standard; calibration cannot be primary
- Feedback loop formalisation: [Ensign et al., Lum and Isaac, Akpinar et al.] --
  iterative prediction systems structurally amplify historical policing bias
- Philosophical fairness frameworks: [Eva, Beigang, Babic and Johnson King, Hu] --
  statistical criteria require normative grounding in antidiscrimination theory
- Proxy discrimination view: [Barocas and Selbst, Dwork et al., Hellman] --
  facially neutral features can systematically encode protected characteristics
====================================================================
}

