  POSITION: Pro-generalisation, defending statistical reasoning in law with moral qualifications.
  },
  keywords = {profiling, stereotypes, actuarial-reasoning, generalisation, book, Medium},
  abstract = {Preface Introduction: Painting with a Broad Brush 1. In Training with the Greeks 2. Pit Bulls, Golden Retrievers, and Other Dangerous Dogs 3. A Ride on the Blue Bus 4. Eighty-Year-Old Pilots and Twelve-Year-Old Voters 5. The Women of the Virginia Military Institute 6. The Profilers 7. The Usual Suspects 8. Two Cheers for Procrustes 9. Ships with Altered Names 10. The Generality of Law 11. Generality, Community, and the Wars of the Roqueforts Coda: From the Justice of Generality to the Generality of Justice Notes Index},
  abstract_source = {s2},
}

@article{hosein2018racial,
  author = {Hosein, Adam Omar},
  title = {Racial Profiling and a Reasonable Sense of Inferior Political Status},
  journal = {Journal of Political Philosophy},
  year = {2018},
  volume = {26},
  number = {3},
  doi = {10.1111/jopp.12162},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Hosein argues that racial profiling wrongs its targets by giving them a reasonable sense of inferior political status -- that they are treated as second-class members of the political community whose equal standing is not respected. This wrong is independent of the epistemic accuracy of the profiling practice: even accurate profiling would convey this message.

  RELEVANCE: By establishing that the wrong of profiling is partially constituted by its expressive political meaning, Hosein's argument is complementary to the project's epistemic critique. The project demolishes the epistemic justification; Hosein shows that there is a residual moral wrong that would persist even if the epistemic problem were solved.

  POSITION: Political-status and expressive-harm theory of the wrong of profiling.
  },
